Gleeson CJ, McHugh and Gummow JJ held ( Cabal 209 CLR at 192 [62]) that, before a judge granted bail, the person whose extradition was sought ordinarily would need to show three things: 

 (1) the application for review had strong prospects of success;
 (2) special circumstances;
 (3) an absence of risk of flight.
